00:06:11,325 --> 00:06:16,529
we really faced a choice of whether to soften Chloe's personality and try to turn her into more

92
00:06:17,129 --> 00:06:23,114
of an open player character, or retain all of her personality, those wonderful rough edges,

93
00:06:23,794 --> 00:06:27,237
and try to find other avenues for bringing the player into the story.

94
00:06:28,858 --> 00:06:31,280
And you can see which one we chose.

95
00:06:34,795 --> 00:06:40,240
So it turned out in the end that having a prescribed player character actually wasn't a hindrance.

96
00:06:40,440 --> 00:06:41,502
It was a massive gift.

97
00:06:42,082 --> 00:06:48,128
Because if we could get the player into the headspace of this very singular character,

98
00:06:48,749 --> 00:06:52,513
we will have achieved, here it comes, empathy.

99
00:06:54,615 --> 00:06:55,536
So how did we do this?

100
00:06:56,256 --> 00:06:57,978
Let's talk about the building blocks.

101
00:07:00,448 --> 00:07:06,469
Not having a power, like Max's rewind ability in the first game, our tools were very, very basic.

102
00:07:06,829 --> 00:07:12,150
We would explore, interact, express ourselves, and make decisions.

103
00:07:13,311 --> 00:07:19,872
So, explore, that's simply pathing around the spaces that Chloe lives in, the spaces that are important to her,

104
00:07:21,752 --> 00:07:24,653
interacting with the objects that reflect her personality,

105
00:07:24,853 --> 00:07:28,774
and being rewarded with her thoughts, and sometimes opportunities for action.

106
00:07:30,823 --> 00:07:33,305
Expressing herself through dialogue,

107
00:07:33,946 --> 00:07:35,187
through dialogue choices,

108
00:07:35,467 --> 00:07:37,068
and through opportunities for play.

109
00:07:39,230 --> 00:07:42,753
And then making decisions, sometimes big decisions,

110
00:07:42,893 --> 00:07:44,715
about her personality, about her morality,

111
00:07:44,855 --> 00:07:46,036
about the people she cares about.

112
00:07:48,158 --> 00:07:50,300
Everything the player did in Before the Storm

113
00:07:50,460 --> 00:07:51,741
was filtered through Chloe.

114
00:07:53,567 --> 00:07:55,988
It's why the most important relationship in the game,

115
00:07:56,148 --> 00:07:58,350
we realized, wasn't between Chloe and Rachel

116
00:07:58,550 --> 00:07:59,910
or anyone else in the story.

117
00:07:59,950 --> 00:08:01,571
It was between the player and Chloe.

118
00:08:01,611 --> 00:08:04,032
That was the relationship we came to care about the most.

119
00:08:05,433 --> 00:08:07,174
With every interaction that we built,

120
00:08:07,674 --> 00:08:09,935
we strove to build out Chloe's interiority.

121
00:08:10,015 --> 00:08:11,396
That's the thing that we focused on.

122
00:08:12,256 --> 00:08:13,557
And hopefully as we did that,

123
00:08:13,717 --> 00:08:16,618
we were bringing the character along with her

124
00:08:16,758 --> 00:08:19,640
into her headspace, cementing that empathic link

125
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:20,380
we were trying to build.

126
00:08:21,532 --> 00:08:26,756
It's one thing to do that when it comes to elements of the story, like rebelling

127
00:08:26,816 --> 00:08:31,759
against your mother's dickish boyfriend or falling for Rachel Amber, hopefully

128
00:08:31,819 --> 00:08:34,741
most players are going to be ready to go along for that ride.

129
00:08:35,742 --> 00:08:39,384
Uh, but it's more challenging when it comes to a deeper and

130
00:08:39,424 --> 00:08:41,325
more complex emotion like grief.

131
00:08:44,487 --> 00:08:49,911
So that's the, the, the foundational, uh, mechanical link between the player.

132
00:08:50,694 --> 00:08:52,715
and the player character in Narrative Adventure,

133
00:08:52,755 --> 00:08:55,195
but we want to focus on something we discovered

134
00:08:55,235 --> 00:08:57,916
in Before the Storm, something that ultimately led

135
00:08:57,976 --> 00:08:59,576
to why we made True Colors at all.

136
00:08:59,596 --> 00:09:02,016
And that's a scene we call Junkyard Smash.

137
00:09:04,037 --> 00:09:05,357
So this is the end of the first episode.

138
00:09:05,377 --> 00:09:08,138
It's building suspense.

139
00:09:09,738 --> 00:09:10,898
Chloe just spent the day

140
00:09:11,058 --> 00:09:12,519
with the most popular girl in school.

141
00:09:12,579 --> 00:09:14,919
Chloe is 16, her father recently died.

142
00:09:14,979 --> 00:09:17,380
She is filled with anger, she is alienated, she's hurt,

143
00:09:17,460 --> 00:09:19,260
and she just had this magical experience

144
00:09:19,300 --> 00:09:19,780
for someone.

145
00:09:20,682 --> 00:09:23,285
opposite to her in every way, took an interest in her life.

146
00:09:24,706 --> 00:09:29,590
And then they arrive at this junkyard, and inexplicably that person turns on her, hurts

147
00:09:29,631 --> 00:09:30,691
her and abandons her.

148
00:09:31,732 --> 00:09:36,136
And we enter the free-roam space where the player now is on the sticks and has control,

149
00:09:36,817 --> 00:09:40,821
with the goal stated to them, fuck this place.

150
00:09:42,894 --> 00:09:47,898
We replace traditional verbs that allow for choice in terms of how you want to interact with the world

151
00:09:48,378 --> 00:09:52,441
with the loud interior voice of Chloe's need to smash things.

152
00:09:53,902 --> 00:09:54,622
And she really does.

153
00:09:56,704 --> 00:10:01,307
In fact, she begins to project the people in her life that have hurt her the most

154
00:10:01,927 --> 00:10:05,250
on the junk that she finds, and she smashes all of it.

155
00:10:05,955 --> 00:10:07,116
A mannequin for Rachel.

156
00:10:07,136 --> 00:10:09,239
A camera for Max.

157
00:10:09,259 --> 00:10:12,883
It's hard to see, but that's a toolbox for David.

158
00:10:12,903 --> 00:10:17,088
And then something magical happens.

159
00:10:18,307 --> 00:10:26,572
Up to this point, the relationship between the player and Chloe is one of spectator and angry girl.

160
00:10:26,912 --> 00:10:30,273
Very few players are feeling the rage she's feeling.

161
00:10:30,394 --> 00:10:38,898
In fact, the playfulness of the verbs themselves frame a kind of entertainment from watching her be angry.

162
00:10:40,799 --> 00:10:43,200
And then she finds her father's car.

163
00:10:44,575 --> 00:10:46,916
And we just found this working on the story,

164
00:10:47,697 --> 00:10:49,118
trying to come up with what would be

