243
00:16:20,411 --> 00:16:21,351
Eleanor's fear together.

244
00:16:21,952 --> 00:16:23,753
So we're going to interact with objects.

245
00:16:24,944 --> 00:16:27,807
that are connected to it, we're gonna hear insights,

246
00:16:28,728 --> 00:16:32,051
and ultimately, we're gonna be inside Eleanor's thoughts

247
00:16:32,471 --> 00:16:35,214
and we're gonna fill out an understanding of that fear,

248
00:16:35,554 --> 00:16:36,495
of that emotion of hers.

249
00:16:38,377 --> 00:16:40,819
Now, once we've explored Eleanor's emotion,

250
00:16:41,079 --> 00:16:42,961
we come away understanding the cause of it,

251
00:16:43,001 --> 00:16:44,923
that she's suffering from dementia

252
00:16:45,223 --> 00:16:47,365
and she feels her grasp on reality slipping away.

253
00:16:48,542 --> 00:16:53,646
And hopefully what we were really going for, the crux of all of the sound design,

254
00:16:53,666 --> 00:16:57,909
the cinematics that you saw, was to try and engender some of that feeling that we

255
00:16:57,949 --> 00:17:03,474
captured with Chloe in the junkyard of not just being the spectator, but

256
00:17:03,794 --> 00:17:05,916
participating in the emotional experience.

257
00:17:06,356 --> 00:17:09,018
Except now it's not just our player characters, right?

258
00:17:09,199 --> 00:17:09,939
It's Eleanor's.

259
00:17:10,199 --> 00:17:15,964
We are through Alex sharing in a different character's emotional experience.

260
00:17:15,984 --> 00:17:17,645
We're projecting our empathy outward.

261
00:17:18,650 --> 00:17:24,755
So now that we've been armed with this connection and this empathy for what Eleanor is going through,

262
00:17:25,295 --> 00:17:29,619
we're set up to make a difficult choice on Eleanor's behalf. Alex realizes that Eleanor

263
00:17:29,739 --> 00:17:35,543
has forgotten her brother's death and is unaware of his funeral that evening.

264
00:17:36,544 --> 00:17:40,347
Do we remind her, even having felt how much pain that's going to cause her?

265
00:17:42,960 --> 00:17:47,245
So all the fundamental tools from before the storm were all there in that experience.

266
00:17:47,285 --> 00:17:48,586
They're just projected outward.

267
00:17:48,706 --> 00:17:50,849
We explore another's world.

268
00:17:51,329 --> 00:17:53,391
We interact with the objects important to them.

269
00:17:53,832 --> 00:17:59,258
We express through another's voice and we make moral decisions that impact them.

270
00:18:01,230 --> 00:18:04,332
We really loved using this power to explore

271
00:18:04,352 --> 00:18:06,753
the empathic connections that games can build.

272
00:18:06,833 --> 00:18:09,295
We loved getting to create power moments

273
00:18:09,475 --> 00:18:11,957
like the Eleanor power moment and explore something

274
00:18:11,997 --> 00:18:14,679
that we would never get to do if we were tied

275
00:18:14,739 --> 00:18:16,960
to just one player character experience.

276
00:18:18,063 --> 00:18:23,427
And when we brought empathy from the meta in Before the Storm to the plot in True Colors,

277
00:18:23,847 --> 00:18:28,049
we came to understand it far better and explore it far deeper than we did before.

278
00:18:28,469 --> 00:18:32,712
The more we explored it and the more we read, we discovered something else about empathy

279
00:18:33,172 --> 00:18:34,213
that really surprised us.

280
00:18:37,034 --> 00:18:37,915
Empathy is complicated.

281
00:18:40,196 --> 00:18:40,616
Who knew that?

282
00:18:41,597 --> 00:18:44,378
Also, just side note, thanks for bearing with us with the tech.

283
00:18:44,418 --> 00:18:45,359
I know it keeps cutting out.

284
00:18:46,722 --> 00:18:50,662
It's GameDevs. I think we're 99% of the time we spend with tech is broken.

285
00:18:51,603 --> 00:18:52,783
So maybe it feels familiar.

286
00:18:53,863 --> 00:18:54,703
Did you plan it that way?

287
00:18:55,563 --> 00:18:56,784
It's not, it's not intentional.

288
00:18:57,744 --> 00:18:59,224
Okay. Yeah, empathy is complicated.

289
00:18:59,584 --> 00:19:00,224
We read a lot.

290
00:19:01,304 --> 00:19:04,445
Organizational psychology, behavioral psychology, social science,

291
00:19:05,105 --> 00:19:06,365
spiritualists, gurus.

292
00:19:08,006 --> 00:19:09,726
Empathy is a bit of a buzzword lately too.

293
00:19:09,886 --> 00:19:11,226
It's a positive. It's a net good.

294
00:19:11,266 --> 00:19:11,827
It's a virtue.

295
00:19:13,255 --> 00:19:16,857
I think often when people talk about the positive elements of empathy, what they're really talking

296
00:19:16,897 --> 00:19:18,338
about is compassion.

297
00:19:19,899 --> 00:19:23,762
Empathy is when someone else's emotional state overrides yours.

298
00:19:26,104 --> 00:19:33,589
When your best friend is mad at you and they say something dumb or a place of anger, what's

299
00:19:33,609 --> 00:19:34,709
the best way to react to that?

300
00:19:36,190 --> 00:19:38,832
It's probably not to immediately be as angry as they are.

301
00:19:39,993 --> 00:19:42,535
It's equally wrong not to pay attention to what's making them angry.

302
00:19:43,560 --> 00:19:44,620
But that's the complication.

303
00:19:44,940 --> 00:19:48,222
That's the thing that really became interesting to us.

304
00:19:50,082 --> 00:19:51,823
So as often happens with story development,

305
00:19:52,103 --> 00:19:55,064
the thematic and conceptual exploration

306
00:19:56,085 --> 00:19:58,526
ultimately came full circle and influenced the plot.

307
00:19:58,726 --> 00:20:00,207
And the entirety of the fifth episode

308
00:20:00,227 --> 00:20:01,387
of True Colors is about this.

309
00:20:03,688 --> 00:20:06,289
So when we end four, Alex gets shot in the head

310
00:20:06,389 --> 00:20:07,370
and thrown down a mine.

311
00:20:10,057 --> 00:20:15,800
She wakes up and she has to, in a very surreal series of exchanges,

312
00:20:16,361 --> 00:20:18,142
perform the empathy power on herself,

313
00:20:19,442 --> 00:20:24,466
and go through constellation points in her life that have wounded her the most,

314
00:20:24,926 --> 00:20:27,808
and that have coded her to be the person she is.

315
00:20:29,289 --> 00:20:31,890
Sadness over her mother's death.

316
00:20:31,910 --> 00:20:36,793
It's the first time we're going to see Alex shooting a Nova out of her own.

317
00:20:38,764 --> 00:20:42,467
the terror when their father abandoned her brother and her.

318
00:20:45,190 --> 00:20:46,451
One of the harder moments in the game,

319
00:20:47,232 --> 00:20:51,035
Alex has to sit in a version of the orphanage

320
00:20:51,075 --> 00:20:53,897
she grew up in and watch as

321
00:20:56,560 --> 00:20:58,862
potentially adopting parents would approach

322
00:20:59,583 --> 00:21:02,645
and she would feel all the reasons they didn't pick her.

323
00:21:05,067 --> 00:21:05,888
And she's sensitive.

324
00:21:07,935 --> 00:21:10,576
I'm sure she's a sweet girl, she hears, but she's not for us.

325
00:21:12,257 --> 00:21:14,119
It's the kid who's been in all those fights, right?

326
00:21:15,479 --> 00:21:20,042
There's just something off, wrong with her.

327
00:21:21,303 --> 00:21:24,645
And we watch Alex explode in anger.

328
00:21:24,665 --> 00:21:27,507
I think it's my favorite shot in the game.

329
00:21:27,527 --> 00:21:28,287
It's really cool.

330
00:21:30,289 --> 00:21:30,849
Why do we do that?

331
00:21:32,788 --> 00:21:36,792
It's because she needs to face the lies she's told herself

332
00:21:37,132 --> 00:21:38,473
because of the wounds she suffered.

333
00:21:38,533 --> 00:21:41,735
She needs to actually practice a kind of self-empathy.

334
00:21:43,417 --> 00:21:46,699
And from that place, she finds peace.

335
00:21:48,280 --> 00:21:50,982
She finds what we discovered in research

336
00:21:51,283 --> 00:21:52,984
is known as emotional self-integrity.

337
00:21:54,565 --> 00:21:55,986
She's contended with her demons,

338
00:21:57,207 --> 00:21:59,769
which puts her in a place where she's actually ready

339
00:21:59,789 --> 00:22:01,150
to deal with other people's.

340
00:22:04,041 --> 00:22:05,122
And that's what the game became about.

341
00:22:05,962 --> 00:22:07,944
It's not to say empathy is bad, empathy is wonderful.

342
00:22:08,224 --> 00:22:09,304
It's an extraordinary thing.

343
00:22:10,245 --> 00:22:12,066
But like most powerful things,

344
00:22:13,487 --> 00:22:15,068
there is risk associated with it.

345
00:22:17,790 --> 00:22:20,372
So what does this mean for narrative adventure

346
00:22:21,132 --> 00:22:22,293
or empathy in storytelling?

347
00:22:24,234 --> 00:22:27,396
MLK says the arc of the universe bends toward justice.

348
00:22:28,705 --> 00:22:36,731
I think the narrative arc of story over the last few thousand years bends toward empathy

349
00:22:36,991 --> 00:22:37,652
in a certain way.

350
00:22:38,332 --> 00:22:40,394
We're striving to get closer to each other.

351
00:22:41,595 --> 00:22:44,037
Why do we love stories so much anyway?

352
00:22:45,098 --> 00:22:46,339
What is it that they provide?

353
00:22:49,341 --> 00:22:50,322
I think they build maps.

354
00:22:51,022 --> 00:22:52,003
It's not my idea, but...

355
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:53,600
A lot of writers think this.

356
00:22:53,660 --> 00:22:54,140
They're maps.

357
00:22:54,300 --> 00:22:55,621
They show us the way to go.

358
00:22:55,681 --> 00:22:58,622
They show us how to find peace in our lives.

359
00:22:58,922 --> 00:23:00,963
That's how a 50-year-old man can play Chloe

360
00:23:01,803 --> 00:23:03,224
and come away from that experience

361
00:23:03,964 --> 00:23:05,945
enriched in his relationship with his dad.

362
00:23:08,466 --> 00:23:11,427
So John, as he often does and has done for years,

363
00:23:11,707 --> 00:23:12,587
challenged me last night.

364
00:23:12,627 --> 00:23:14,548
He said the best talks he's seen at GDC

365
00:23:15,849 --> 00:23:17,769
conclude with some kind of call to action.

366
00:23:19,050 --> 00:23:20,931
And he asked like, what's our call to action?

367
00:23:20,971 --> 00:23:21,471
We didn't have one.

368
00:23:22,644 --> 00:23:24,765
We were just making a presentation about empathy

369
00:23:24,865 --> 00:23:26,646
and I thought a lot about it.

370
00:23:26,886 --> 00:23:29,747
And I don't think it was until right before this talk

371
00:23:29,767 --> 00:23:32,329
that I realized what I wanted to kind of end on.

372
00:23:36,471 --> 00:23:40,152
And I, pardon me for how dark this may sound,

373
00:23:40,192 --> 00:23:42,473
especially when the Wordle presentation

374
00:23:42,493 --> 00:23:43,254
is applauding right now.

375
00:23:45,855 --> 00:23:47,816
Something I think a lot about as an entertainer

376
00:23:47,976 --> 00:23:50,917
and as a game designer is the state of our kids.

377
00:23:53,101 --> 00:23:54,962
I think our kids are in a certain kind of crisis.

378
00:23:57,683 --> 00:23:59,323
More than any other generation in history,

379
00:23:59,964 --> 00:24:01,084
they are involved with tech.

380
00:24:02,185 --> 00:24:04,486
They deal with interactive media every day

381
00:24:05,286 --> 00:24:08,707
and more hours a day than we did when we were young.

382
00:24:11,048 --> 00:24:15,890
And anxiety, depression, suicidal ideation,

383
00:24:16,290 --> 00:24:20,212
and loneliness, loneliness are at all time highs.

384
00:24:23,444 --> 00:24:28,806
And I'm not a doctor, few game devs are, and I don't know the answer to this, but

385
00:24:28,886 --> 00:24:36,549
surely a part of it has to be that the places we build as devs, it's what we do.

386
00:24:36,569 --> 00:24:37,049
We're builders.

387
00:24:38,070 --> 00:24:41,291
The digital places we build are places that strengthen.

388
00:24:42,939 --> 00:24:46,622
There are places that teach emotional self-integrity.

389
00:24:47,964 --> 00:24:51,427
And from there, how to love across difference

390
00:24:51,487 --> 00:24:53,208
and how to build meaningful relationships

391
00:24:53,789 --> 00:24:56,611
and how to practice empathy in a healthy way.

392
00:24:58,073 --> 00:24:59,614
That's my hope for what we can do.

393
00:24:59,654 --> 00:25:01,456
I think that's my call to action.

394
00:25:02,537 --> 00:25:02,877
Thank you.

395
00:25:04,499 --> 00:25:04,959
Thanks, everyone.

396
00:25:15,103 --> 00:25:19,905
We have lots of time for questions, so please come ask them.

397
00:25:20,305 --> 00:25:22,526
We have microphones on both sides.

398
00:25:25,927 --> 00:25:29,489
Oh, there we go. Okay.

399
00:25:29,809 --> 00:25:33,510
Hi, my name's Eric, and I was late, but great talk.

400
00:25:34,591 --> 00:25:38,513
Um, it's not exactly a question, it's more of an endorsement actually.

401
00:25:38,833 --> 00:25:41,274
Um, I think you guys are doing great work. I think...

402
00:25:41,874 --> 00:25:44,696
I haven't played this game, but I really want to.

403
00:25:45,576 --> 00:25:48,077
And as game developers, we don't have time to play games.

404
00:25:48,697 --> 00:25:50,078
And we just spoiled the ending for you.

405
00:25:50,458 --> 00:25:52,259
No, I know, right? I'm just like, holy shit.

406
00:25:52,679 --> 00:25:54,300
But, um, is everyone here, uh...

407
00:25:55,744 --> 00:26:01,069
I have a solution and I'm going to implement it one day and anyone wants to come along

408
00:26:01,089 --> 00:26:01,469
the journey.

409
00:26:01,970 --> 00:26:05,593
I actually volunteer on a suicide and crisis hotline and I've been doing that for about

410
00:26:05,653 --> 00:26:06,093
two years.

411
00:26:06,113 --> 00:26:14,300
I've got about 500 hours and if the stars align and if everything works out, I would

412
00:26:14,360 --> 00:26:22,147
like to make some sort of roleplaying suicide and hotline game to encourage everyone to

413
00:26:23,790 --> 00:26:27,414
have empathy for our fellow human beings and our struggles.

414
00:26:28,856 --> 00:26:30,498
And if anyone's interested in that,

415
00:26:30,538 --> 00:26:32,960
they can contact me later.

416
00:26:33,020 --> 00:26:33,481
What's your name?

417
00:26:33,801 --> 00:26:36,184
My name's Eric Chow from Honor Games.

418
00:26:36,664 --> 00:26:36,985
Thank you.

419
00:26:37,005 --> 00:26:38,326
Yeah, thanks for sharing.

420
00:26:41,450 --> 00:26:42,130
Any other questions?

421
00:26:42,170 --> 00:26:43,091
We probably have time for one.

422
00:26:45,036 --> 00:26:51,220
Great talk. I'm curious, like you depict kind of like the inside of the head of very different characters.

423
00:26:51,801 --> 00:26:57,285
And what was your process to depict them authentically and the state of mind that they're going through?

424
00:26:57,305 --> 00:27:07,292
Yeah, I can start on that. We spent a lot of time, a lot of time, a lot of thought, a lot of reading, a lot of talking.

425
00:27:08,393 --> 00:27:10,455
We have a writer's room. There's a talk.

426
00:27:11,456 --> 00:27:13,857
a few days ago about the importance of writers room.

427
00:27:13,957 --> 00:27:16,119
Maybe some of you were in that, yeah.

428
00:27:16,619 --> 00:27:18,560
Yeah, our experience validates that.

429
00:27:19,140 --> 00:27:25,504
You need a team of a diverse set of experiences

430
00:27:25,584 --> 00:27:27,745
and perspectives to come together

431
00:27:28,185 --> 00:27:33,848
and consider something as nuanced and important

432
00:27:34,489 --> 00:27:38,251
as the topics that we hope to deal with.

433
00:27:39,822 --> 00:27:47,467
So I always think about exploding the idea of write what you know and changing it to

434
00:27:47,487 --> 00:27:48,507
know what you write, you know?

435
00:27:49,128 --> 00:27:58,774
As a writer you have to feel a sense of not that you are ever a master with these topics

436
00:27:59,014 --> 00:28:00,455
because how can you be?

437
00:28:00,755 --> 00:28:05,618
But just that you know that you have immersed yourself to a point where.

438
00:28:06,384 --> 00:28:09,690
where you feel comfortable being able to be in that world.

439
00:28:09,730 --> 00:28:11,653
And if you don't, then you have a writer's room

440
00:28:11,873 --> 00:28:14,417
to help you and share that burden.

441
00:28:16,320 --> 00:28:16,721
Thank you.

442
00:28:17,262 --> 00:28:17,703
Yeah, thank you.

443
00:28:18,945 --> 00:28:19,285
Yeah, please.

444
00:28:20,305 --> 00:28:27,490
So you gave the example of the junkyard scene where what the player's doing and what the

445
00:28:27,510 --> 00:28:31,473
player's feeling doesn't really match what the character's feeling and that was kind of

446
00:28:31,533 --> 00:28:36,657
intentional because you brought it together later on. I'm wondering if there were any moments

447
00:28:37,778 --> 00:28:42,181
you have in mind where the player was unintentionally not feeling

448
00:28:43,082 --> 00:28:47,485
in line with what the character was feeling and what kinds of things you did to address that?

449
00:28:50,322 --> 00:28:50,983
Do you stand by that?

450
00:28:51,483 --> 00:28:53,724
I mean, the first time we introduced Alex's power

451
00:28:53,764 --> 00:28:57,466
in True Colors, it's deliberately off-putting,

452
00:28:57,506 --> 00:28:59,407
strange, shocking, kind of overwhelming.

453
00:28:59,487 --> 00:29:01,387
She flips out in anger and beats a guy up

454
00:29:01,467 --> 00:29:02,388
and kind of ruins her day.

455
00:29:02,408 --> 00:29:06,370
We were doing that to put the, on two levels.

456
00:29:06,410 --> 00:29:08,170
Like on one level, you know,

457
00:29:08,210 --> 00:29:09,551
you're not angry and punching Mac.

458
00:29:09,751 --> 00:29:10,411
You're not doing that.

459
00:29:10,511 --> 00:29:11,352
That's not what's happening.

460
00:29:12,512 --> 00:29:13,573
So you're like, what the fuck?

461
00:29:13,773 --> 00:29:17,435
But then neither is Alex.

462
00:29:18,677 --> 00:29:21,218
Like, Alex is also like, what the hell?

463
00:29:21,338 --> 00:29:22,419
Like, what did I just do?

464
00:29:22,439 --> 00:29:24,300
I don't have control either.

465
00:29:24,320 --> 00:29:26,080
And I think we found a harmony there.

466
00:29:26,100 --> 00:29:27,801
We were a little bit concerned at that.

467
00:29:27,921 --> 00:29:29,062
And there were voices on the team

468
00:29:29,122 --> 00:29:30,463
who thought that would be really off-putting.

469
00:29:30,963 --> 00:29:32,564
But then we just leaned in and we decided

470
00:29:32,584 --> 00:29:34,005
that's actually a pretty interesting way

471
00:29:34,065 --> 00:29:35,986
to engender a closer connection

472
00:29:36,006 --> 00:29:37,987
between the player and Alex out of the gate.

473
00:29:38,427 --> 00:29:39,367
Yeah, I think also...

474
00:29:40,195 --> 00:29:44,220
You know, we have different language that we use to talk about this idea.

475
00:29:44,540 --> 00:29:48,865
Like, we're always talking about where's the player and where's the player character, and

476
00:29:48,905 --> 00:29:50,727
how close are they, and when are they separate.

477
00:29:51,027 --> 00:29:54,471
And the answer isn't always that they have to be in lockstep with each other.

478
00:29:54,811 --> 00:29:59,777
Sometimes, like I think the junkyard scene is actually an example of this, you can find

479
00:30:00,357 --> 00:30:00,858
a greater...

480
00:30:02,520 --> 00:30:08,846
harmony by beginning from a place of dissonance, because you can't expect the player to be right

481
00:30:08,886 --> 00:30:14,831
there with your player character experiencing something difficult or unique right at the

482
00:30:14,851 --> 00:30:21,998
beginning of the scene. But that's where we get to use our tools and create a sense of play to draw

483
00:30:22,038 --> 00:30:25,782
the player into it. So I think, you know, there's almost a musicality to it, where you can think

484
00:30:25,822 --> 00:30:26,983
about like a dissonance.

485
00:30:27,604 --> 00:30:34,048
and an assonance that builds over the course of a sequence where you hopefully land at

486
00:30:34,068 --> 00:30:39,973
a place that comes together and finds that poignancy.

487
00:30:39,993 --> 00:30:41,554
I think we have time for one more question.

488
00:30:42,495 --> 00:30:47,539
And then I want to remind everyone I was asked to remind you to fill out your surveys about

489
00:30:47,559 --> 00:30:48,239
the quality of the talk.

